== Hot Spring Town == Located along the {{ill|Tokachi River|ja|十勝川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokachi River|qq=}} and {{ill|Hokkaido Route 73|ja|北海道道現73号線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkaido Route 73|qq=}}, the hot spring town features several facilities, including {{ill|Michi-no-Eki Garden Spa Tokachigawa Onsen|ja|道の駅ガーデンスパ十勝川温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Michi-no-Eki Garden Spa Tokachigawa Onsen|qq=}}.{{Cite web|url=http://www.tokachigawa.jp |title=道の駅ガーデンスパ十勝川温泉 |accessdate=2020-10-23}} Other attractions include footbaths and year-round outdoor activities organized by the Tokachi Nature Center.{{Cite web|url=http://www.nature-tokachi.co.jp |title=十勝ネイチャーセンター |accessdate=2015-06-15}}
== History == The onsen's historical record dates back to 1874 when it was mentioned in "Hokkaido Chishi Youryo" as "Otogawa Yu." Initially utilized by local Ainu people as "medicine water," the modern history of Tokachigawa Onsen began in 1900 when Kahei Iba redirected lukewarm water into a wooden box for communal use. By 1913, Touzaburo Maeda developed the area, discovering higher-temperature springs through digging efforts.{{Cite web|url=http://www.sasaihotel.com/gensen/ |title=筋温泉物語 |work=Hotel Sasai |accessdate=2015-06-15}}
== Events ==
Tokachigawa Swan Festival "Sairinka" (Late January - Late February)
Footpath Walking Event (June)
Flower Landscape "Hanack and Flower Road" (Late June - Late July)
Autumn Festa in Tokachigawa (Early October - Early November)
== Access ==
JR {{ill|Nemuro Main Line|ja|根室本線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nemuro Main Line|qq=}}, Obihiro Station, 20 minutes by car.{{Cite web|url=http://www.tokachigawa.net/access/ |title=アクセス |publisher=Tokachigawa Onsen Tourism Association |accessdate=2015-06-15}}
From Tokachigawa IC (Dōto Expressway), 25 minutes by car.
